<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>so long as workers have the option of working it or not<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Just can't/won't ever be true.<br>
<br>
If the company is only offering straight-time for overtime and Joe isn't willing to work overtime while Jim, on the other hand, is, then what happens to Joe?<br>
<br>
Same thing that happens now, that's what. Overtime is almost always voluntary, but the guy who isn't willing to do it 'isn't a team player' or something like that. Give companies the option of paying someone less money for something that isn't *really*, ie. it comes back to haunt you, and you're just opening the floodgates for all kinds of abuse.<br>
<br>
Salaried employees, however, is a whole different thing.<br>
